<DOC><DOCNO> SJMN91-06315236 </DOCNO><ACCESS> 06315236 </ACCESS><CAPTION>  Photo; PHOTO: Associated Press; INTREPID -- A driver undeterred by flooding inthe Outer Banks area plows through high water on a road on Hatteras Island,N.C., which was closed soon after the driver passed.  </CAPTION><DESCRIPT>  NORTH-CAROLINA; WEATHER; FORECAST; REPORT  </DESCRIPT><LEADPARA>  A fierce Atlantic storm Saturday lashed North Carolina's Outer Banks withstrong wind and crashing waves that pounded through sand dunes shieldingoceanfront homes. Residents fought back with sand bags and bulldozers.;   Therest of the East Coast braced for the wintry onslaught, less than two weeksafter another storm pummeled the region. In the Midwest, meanwhile, an Arcticcold front brought record low temperatures and freezing rains.  </LEADPARA><SECTION>  Front  </SECTION><HEADLINE>  STORM SLAMS N.C. COAST; COLD FRONT HITS MIDWEST  </HEADLINE><TEXT>     The Atlantic storm, brewing off the South Carolina coast, blasted theshoreline with 50-mph gusts.;   As the storm churned, Outer Banks residentsdeployed bulldozers and laid out sandbags where dunes had shielded their homesuntil late last month.;   In Kitty Hawk, N.C., where the roiling ocean stoppedjust short of a road, Town Manager Robert Nicholl said police and fireofficials were exhausted after 10 days of working around the clock to clearstreets of sand, debris and water.;   &quot;It's going to be miserable, at best,&quot;said Buddy Shelton, emergency management director in Dare County, N.C.;  North Carolina's mountains received 3 inches of snow. It was welcome at theAppalachian Ski Mountain near Blowing Rock in the Blue Ridge Mountains.General manager Grady Moretz started his season Saturday using snow machinesto supplement the real thing. It was the earliest opening in his 30 years inthe business, he said.;   Freezing rain extended from Montana to Minnesota.Low-temperature records fell in dozens of cities.;   Freezing rain turned manyNorth Dakota roads into sheets of ice Saturday, and residents in the easternpart of the state were advised not to travel.;   &quot;We've got the world'sbiggest skating rink up here, and I don't think it's going to get any betteruntil tomorrow,&quot; said Wells County Sheriff Curtis Pellett said.;   The stormforecast included slim prospects of rain reaching southern West Virginia, thearea of the state hardest hit by wildfires. More than 1,000 fires havescorched 337,000 acres in the Appalachian region since Oct. 26.  </TEXT><BYLINE>  Associated Press  </BYLINE><COUNTRY>  USA  </COUNTRY><EDITION>  Morning Final  </EDITION><CODE>  SJ  </CODE><NAME>  San Jose Mercury News  </NAME><PUBDATE>   911110  </PUBDATE> <DAY>  Sunday  </DAY><MONTH>  November  </MONTH><PG.COL>  14A  </PG.COL><PUBYEAR>  1991  </PUBYEAR><REGION>  WEST  </REGION><FEATURE>  PHOTO  </FEATURE><STATE>  CA  </STATE><WORD.CT>  358  </WORD.CT><DATELINE>  Sunday, November 10, 199100315236,SJ1  </DATELINE><COPYRGHT>  Copyright 1991, San Jose Mercury News  </COPYRGHT><LIMLEN>  1  </LIMLEN><LANGUAGE>  ENG  </LANGUAGE></DOC>